{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567659"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:05:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19220"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19220"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.75,0.1,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11954"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11954"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67431"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"1325"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"11464"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three days of worsening mid-thoracic back pain and progressive weakness in both legs. He has a history of prostate cancer diagnosed two years ago and is currently receiving androgen deprivation therapy. His other medical conditions include hypertension. His medications include goserelin, amlodipine, and paracetamol. On examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals reduced power (3/5) in both lower limbs with increased tone and hyperreflexia. There is a sensory level at T8 and urinary retention. Upper limb examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial imaging investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT spine","MRI spine","Plain X-ray spine","Nuclear bone scan","CT-PET scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of metastatic spinal cord compression, a medical emergency that requires immediate intervention to prevent permanent neurological damage. The history of prostate cancer (which commonly metastasises to bone), progressive back pain, and neurological deficits with a sensory level are classic presenting features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI spine\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard imaging modality for suspected cord compression. It provides excellent visualisation of soft tissues, including the spinal cord and nerve roots, and can demonstrate the extent of compression and any epidural disease. The entire spine should be imaged as there may be multiple levels of compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT spine\u003C/strong\u003E can show bony metastases but is inferior to MRI in demonstrating cord compression and soft tissue involvement. It may be useful if MRI is contraindicated or unavailable, but it is not the first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain X-ray spine\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in suspected cord compression. While it may show vertebral collapse or lytic lesions, it cannot demonstrate neural compression and may appear normal despite significant cord compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuclear bone scan\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for detecting bone metastases but cannot demonstrate cord compression. It is more appropriate for staging or surveillance rather than acute cord compression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT-PET scan\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for detecting metastatic disease but is not the appropriate first-line investigation for suspected cord compression due to limited availability and inability to clearly demonstrate neural compression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metastatic spinal cord compression is an oncological emergency requiring immediate corticosteroids and urgent MRI.","Back pain with neurological symptoms in a patient with cancer should be treated as cord compression until proven otherwise.","Early recognition and treatment of cord compression improves neurological outcomes.","MRI is the gold standard imaging modality for suspected cord compression as it best demonstrates soft tissue and neural compression."],"references":["Ropper AE, Ropper AH. Acute Spinal Cord Compression. N Engl J Med. 2017 Apr 6;376(14):1358\u201369. Available at https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28379788/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67431"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19220"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67431"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-28T20:55:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-28T20:56:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11954"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82233"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}